    <p>The author describes an R package that displays discrete and continuous data onto anatomical structures. The structures are based on mouse and human anatograms from the Expression Atlas project and the grammar from ggplot2 R library. The code example was easy to run and the necessary input data was intuitive and simple. </p>
    <p> The author can increase its usage by providing a webtool (even one based on shiny) that takes as input a csv or tsv table with predefined columns. This would allow physicians and scientists with no background in bioinformatics to easily display their data. </p>
